<span id="freeTextContainer17969806107530328203">Dedicated to Manuel Alfonseca <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1117598.Manuel_Alfonseca'>https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a><br/>I am writing this review for several reasons, but the main is to welcome the writer Manuel Alfonseca, who will return from Portugal between today and tomorrow. Also led me to write this review the interest of Mr Jeremy Forsyth (I think, that are dying to know my opinion of this book) <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/16865044.Jeremy_Forsyth'>https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> and also by the writer José Baena Castel https:// <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14185125.Jos_Baena_Castel'>www.goodreads.com/author/show/1418512...</a><br/>(I think, I do</span>
  <span id="freeText17969806107530328203" style="display:none">Dedicated to Manuel Alfonseca <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1117598.Manuel_Alfonseca">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a><br />I am writing this review for several reasons, but the main is to welcome the writer Manuel Alfonseca, who will return from Portugal between today and tomorrow. Also led me to write this review the interest of Mr Jeremy Forsyth (I think, that are dying to know my opinion of this book) <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/16865044.Jeremy_Forsyth">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> and also by the writer José Baena Castel https:// <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14185125.Jos_Baena_Castel">www.goodreads.com/author/show/1418512...</a><br />(I think, I do not ask, but I wanted to do it). <br />The first advice that I give to people who want to learn the readings of Lois McMaster Bujold is that they do not like me and begin the sagas by the principle. If you are interested in her Miles Vorkosigan saga begin by "Warrior's Apprentice", and in the case of the world of the five gods who do not like me that I started by the "sacred quest" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/22397034-la-b-squeda-sagrada?ac=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2...</a> &amp; from_search = true<br />and I found not clear out of the peculiarities of the magical universe of Lois Mcmaster Bujold. First thing that I note is the benign influence of the writer Patricia C. Wredde had (hopefully to be edited to him something in Spain part of the Star Wars Episode I already have a publisher sent a list of names recommending certain writers) , but I think, that they will do me any case :-() <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/36122.Patricia_C_Wrede">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> who sent him a collection of journals in history, Lois Mcmaster Bujold helped create its universe. Whoever wants to know the coincidences between the world of Chalion and the history of our country at the end of the 15th century I recommend reading this brilliant article by Manuel Alfonseca <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://divulciencia.blogspot.com/2015/04/maldicion-de-chalion.html">divulciencia.blogspot.com/2015/04/mal...</a><br />However although this history is very inspired by the end of the 15th century, and Bergón and Iselle are inspired by the Catholic monarchs, it is only an inspiration has not thought fantastic key write the history of our country. I thank Lois Mcmaster Bujold have been inspired by an episode of our history, and have not fallen into the themes of the black legend, because it was the simplest. Because Spain has many attractive things, William Goldman gave that nationality to the mythical Iñigo Montoya in his hilarious novel "The Princess Bride" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/21787.The_Princess_Bride?ac=1">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2...</a> &amp; from_search = true<br />In a world similar to the end of the 15th century Castile well recreated by Lois Mcmaster Bujold highlighted with strength the figure of Lupe Cazaril, and as an apparently heinous finding will make acting force of Providence. Because there is one thing, having in common Cazaril with the characters of Margaret Weiss and Tracy Hickman <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/868.Tracy_Hickman">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7275581.Margaret_Weiss">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a><br />and Cazaril is a Christ figure. I don't know if any other author previously part of Tracy Hickman, or Margaret Weiss has used it before, but I have seen it was for the first time to these writers. Something of interest is precisely the interesting theology of the world of the five gods, and the ideas of the characters on the power of good and evil. On the issue of the fight with the Roknaris we see this follow a different religion than the different kingdoms of this world. That world is a reverse of the Iberian Peninsula map. Another thing that may like is the vision that has Lois Mcmaster Bujold of the policy, as of diplomacy in this universe, as in his novels of science fiction starring thousands Vorkosigan <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/series/98250-vorkosigan-saga-publication">https://www.goodreads.com/series/9825...</a> We see that the politics and diplomacy have a great weight. The characters in this case if it is thousands move by the corrupt world of Barrayar, Cazaril, and Iselle moved by Cardegoss without staining, or corrupted indeed is fascinating, as it features Lois Mcmaster Bujold evil in the universe of the five gods in this case by m middle of a curse by a King, that looks like Alfonso X (but it is not). Unlike the Grimdark characters (this term just know recently thanks to Pol Gines, a writer whose name I've figured out, but I will refer to it by its name in Facebook Ana Estelwen, who by the way even I have a pizza :-)). The contrast between how behaves Cazaril, and Miles Vorkosigan (Vorkosigan is one of the three examples that the pro-life can be used in the world of fantasy against abortion, because he was born with a physical disability, other examples are Tanis of the universe of the) Dragonlance product of a violation (although it seems that in the end it wasn't for both), and "crepusculo" Rynesme that have it meant the the death of a mother. These characters according to the legislation in force law Aido, not that of 1985 not would have been born). It is interesting to compare the forms that have to behave before the power both Vorkosigan, and in this case Cazaril, Iselle, and Bergón, not looking for power at any price as the characters in "Song of sky fire" could make it and there is no violence as high as in the novels of Abercrombie, Moorcock, or everyone is going to theirs as the Conan universe, and why the villains as Lord Dondo, and Chancellor Jironal are very evil. McMaster Bujold opts for a different "Prince" of Machiavelli that the modern world scheme. In fact, this was politics that Isabel, followed while her husband more Fox served as a model to the "Prince" Although it is dedicated to Cesar Borgia (except for Isabel, and the Queen Hedwig in Poland the monarchs of that time were very similar). Anyway, nobody writes as well in diplomacy as Lois Mcmaster Bujold. Other characters are superbly well built particularly charming to me Umegat (the most interesting acquisition of the Zoo), be sure to feel some penalty for the fate of Sanda that amgo metapatas, that acts of wrong form with the best intention in the world. One feels sympathy for the Royina Ista, also Bergón and Iselle resemble his manners. Maybe I felt something more disappointed with the villains, although Dondo seems to me to be more evil than his brother Hartou Jironal. However, it would have been more interesting to that for Jironal Hartou I had interest in Felipe Gonzaga's "The hunchback" of Paul Féval <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/401097.Paul_F_val_p_re">https://www.goodreads.com/author/show...</a> <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/759450.Le_Bossu?ac=1&amp;from_search=true">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7...</a> , and if I wanted to evil had recommended the villains of Brent Weeks of his Night Angel trilogy, except where lack bad grapes. Although the hesitant, and fanciful seaside is superbly managed, also Ias Ibra Fox (his fight with Prince reflects what happened in the 15th century Aragon), and any character that does not come out, but it shows his elongated shadow as Lutez (Don Álvaro de Luna) the character of Teidez, as anyone young, inexperienced, and destroyed by the y the power of evil is also very well captured. The first part is magniifica, and is read at a stretch (I have to blame one thing factory of Ideas, and it is that as well as some Spanish publishers split the books into two, to win dineto. I read "The Zangre Ravens", but I was not knowing what was happening until I bought the complete novel). The second costs a lot more to read it, but I was not knowing what was happening until I bought the complete novel). The second costs a lot more to read it, but there are fascinating moments as the dialogue between Liberals and Cazaril, as a bad spiritual takes a physical form (this passage s... I recommend it read any doctor). The reunion between Cazaril, and Rose Bergón is also fascinating. But becomes a tad more difficult, and one of the few flaws that I have to say that it has) the novel is that the end is rushed the story is better. I would have liked to see Iselle fighting against an illegitimate daughter of seaside managed by of Jironal, but this does not offer him us Lois Mcmaster Bujold, who prefers to focus on the sacrifice of Cazaril (I understand it, because of that it is a history of fall sacrifice and redemption). Anyway, the idea is most successful in which for me is the novel's most successful modern fantasy "Brave Story" <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/123557.Brave_Story?ac=1&amp;from_search=true">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1...</a> Miyuki Miyabe, where also two characters in a world must die to save the real world and the magical, and the character while not asked so much as Cazaril (a christic figure, is not Christ, but possesses some of his attributes) Wataru Mitani must renounce to your your dream to do what is right. As conclusion is an outstanding novel about the role of the gods, and its role in addressing evil, and because there is evil and suffering in the world. Perhaps it would have deserved four stars, but I recognize that I was somewhat stingy in assessing "The sacred quest", and I also liked that Lois Mcmaster Bujold has inspired my country and its history to create his fantasy universe. That Yes in the following reading Ms. Bujold will be harder;-). Thank you, Clara María read this novel with me and expect me when you left me behind. I do not know if this will be one of the ten best novels of this year, for those who know have at Cazaril, which is a holy man, who makes miracles;-).</span>
